no specialized handler matches, but for models with well-known fixed formats (like Mistral
Instruct v0.3), a direct string-building handler is more reliable and avoids Jinja rendering
quirks.

The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format uses `[INST]`/`[/INST]` markers (distinct from Ministral 3
which uses `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`). No existing handler covers it, so we need to add one.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `common/chat.cpp` | All edits go here — new handler function + detection logic |
| `common/chat.h` | Read-only — `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` already exists (line 148) |

---

## Implementation

### Step 1 — Add the handler function

**Location:** Insert immediately before `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` at line 1634 in
`common/chat.cpp`.

Add this static function:

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    // Build prompt following Mistral Instruct v0.3 format:
    //   <s>[INST] {system}\n{user1} [/INST] {assistant1}</s>[INST] {user2} [/INST]
    std::string prompt;
    std::string system_content;
    bool        first_user = true;

    for (const auto & msg : inputs.messages) {
        auto role    = msg.value("role", "");
        auto content = msg.value("content", "");

        if (role == "system") {
            system_content = content;
        } else if (role == "user") {
            std::string user_text = content;
            if (first_user && !system_content.empty()) {
                user_text = system_content + "\n" + content;
            }
            first_user = false;
            prompt += "[INST] " + user_text + " [/INST]";
        } else if (role == "assistant") {
            prompt += " " + content + "</s>";
        }
    }

    data.prompt = tmpl.bos_token() + prompt;
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;

    return data;
}
```

**Key design decisions:**
- Uses `msg.value("role", "")` and `msg.value("content", "")` — consistent with all other handlers
- System content is prepended to the **first user turn only**, separated by `\n`
- If no system message exists, user turns are formatted without it
- `tmpl.bos_token()` is used for `<s>` — keeps the handler model-agnostic
- No PEG parser, grammar, or tool-call logic — format is `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY`

### Step 2 — Register detection logic

**Location:** Inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`, just before the final
`return std::nullopt;` at line 1690.

Add the detection block after the GigaChatV3 block (after line 1688):

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v3 - uses [INST]/[/INST] markers without [SYSTEM_PROMPT] special token
    // Detection: presence of [INST] and [/INST] but NOT [SYSTEM_PROMPT] (which Ministral 3 uses)
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos && src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Why this detection is correct:**
- Ministral 3 template has `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, `[TOOL_CALLS]`, and `[ARGS]` — already matched
  by the first block in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` before we're reached
- Our check explicitly excludes `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` as a belt-and-suspenders guard
- `[INST]`/`[/INST]` are unique to the Mistral Instruct family

